2026-04-07 | Walking Robot Simulation II

Question:
•	A robot moves along the **boundary of a grid**.  
•	It starts at (0,0) facing **East**.  
•	If it hits a boundary:
		it turns **counterclockwise (left)** and continues.  

•	So effectively:
		the robot keeps walking along the **perimeter**.

•	Key idea:
		robot movement is **cyclic** along boundary.

	Approach
1.	Compute perimeter length:
		perimeter = 2*(width + height) - 4  

2.	Reduce steps:
		num %= perimeter  

3.	Simulate movement step-by-step:
		try moving in current direction  
		if invalid → turn left  

4.	Track:
		position (x, y)  
		direction index  

	Direction mapping:
		0 → East  
		1 → North  
		2 → West  
		3 → South  

	Time Complexity
	O(perimeter) per step call  

	Space Complexity
	O(1)

	Solution

class Robot {
public:
    int w, h;
    int x = 0, y = 0;
    int dir = 0; // 0:E, 1:N, 2:W, 3:S

    vector<pair<int,int>> d = {
        {1,0},   // East
        {0,1},   // North
        {-1,0},  // West
        {0,-1}   // South
    };

    Robot(int width, int height) {
        w = width;
        h = height;
    }

    void step(int num) {

        int perimeter = 2*(w + h) - 4;
        num %= perimeter;

        while(num--){

            int nx = x + d[dir].first;
            int ny = y + d[dir].second;

            if(nx < 0 || ny < 0 || nx >= w || ny >= h){
                dir = (dir + 1) % 4; // turn left
                num++; // retry step
            }
            else{
                x = nx;
                y = ny;
            }
        }
    }

    vector<int> getPos() {
        return {x, y};
    }

    string getDir() {
        if(dir == 0) return "East";
        if(dir == 1) return "North";
        if(dir == 2) return "West";
        return "South";
    }
};

	Key Insight
The robot never enters inner cells → it always walks on the **boundary loop**.  

So:
		movement becomes cyclic  
		→ optimize using modulo perimeter  

This avoids large step simulations efficiently.
